isible"&gt;w-against-the-alternative-remedies&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Personal blog:&lt;br/&gt;&lt;a href="https://davidallengreen.com/2024/10/a-blow-against-the-alternative-remedies-excuse-the-uk-supreme-court-makes-it-far-harder-for-regulators-to-avoid-performing-their-public-law-duties/" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" translate="no"&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;https://&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="ellipsis"&gt;davidallengreen.com/2024/10/a-&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;blow-against-the-alternative-remedies-excuse-the-uk-supreme-court-makes-it-far-harder-for-regulators-to-avoid-performing-their-public-law-duties/&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</description><guid isPermaLink="false">113350576270678015</guid><pubDate>Tue, 22 Oct 2024 10:22:13 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Richard Van Noorden</title><link>https://mastodon.social/@richvn/113352862078420724</link><description>Which scientific publishers/journals are worst affected by fraudulent or dubious research papers, and which have done least to clean up their portfolio? &lt;br/&gt;A science-integrity startup called Argos says it has answers. &lt;br/&gt;There are quite a few integrity tools now that look for red flags in papers, but this is the first to go public with what it's finding across journals and publishers. &lt;br/&gt;Here's my exclusive look at their figures. &lt;br/&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-024-03427-w" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" translate="no"&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;https://www.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="ellipsis"&gt;nature.com/articles/d41586-024&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;-03427-w&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</description><guid isPermaLink="false">113352972457832544</guid><pubDate>Tue, 22 Oct 2024 20:31:36 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Richard Sever</title><link>https://mas.to/@richardsever/113357666804898010</link><description>"The author disambiguation problem is the single biggest problem the industry has‚ÄùAuthor verification may ultimately be a bigger problem... &lt;a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-024-03427-w" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" translate="no"&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;https://www.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="ellipsis"&gt;nature.com/articles/d41586-024&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;-03427-w&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</description><guid isPermaLink="false">113358222250535803</guid><pubDate>Wed, 23 Oct 2024 18:46:41 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Vittoria Pirone üá™üá∫</title><link>https://mastodon.social/@Vittoria/113358575001251458</link><description>Dominique &lt;a class="mention hashtag" href="https://mastodon.social/tags/Pelicot" rel="tag"&gt;#&lt;span&gt;Pelicot&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt; has admitted to drugging his wife and recruiting dozens of men online to &lt;a class="mention hashtag" href="https://mastodon.social/tags/rape" rel="tag"&gt;#&lt;span&gt;rape&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt; her while she was unconscious and 50 men are facing trial alongside him. Despite video evidence against them, at least 35 of the defendants have denied the rape charges, claiming that Pelicot tricked them into believing they were taking part in a sex game, or that Gisele Pelicot was feigning sleep. Cynthia Illouz, founder of "The Women's Voices," speaks to FRANCE 24. &lt;a class="mention hashtag" href="https://mastodon.social/tags/France" rel="tag"&gt;#&lt;span&gt;France&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YCoDtYlGOhA" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" translate="no"&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;https://www.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="ellipsis"&gt;youtube.com/watch?v=YCoDtYlGOh&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;A&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</description><guid isPermaLink="false">113359020072790179</guid><pubDate>Wed, 23 Oct 2024 22:09:35 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Richard Sever</title><link>https://mas.to/@richardsever/113363182